 femoris","Short head of biceps femoris","Skin over anterolateral leg"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sciatic nerve is the largest nerve in the human body and is composed of two divisions: the tibial division and the common fibular division. These divisions are responsible for both motor and sensory innervation to various parts of the lower limb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is the \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior compartment of the leg except short head of biceps femoris\u003C/strong\u003E. The tibial division of the sciatic nerve provides sensory innervation to the posterior compartment of the leg, excluding the short head of the biceps femoris, which is innervated by the common fibular division.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHamstring portion of adductor magnus\u003C/strong\u003E - This is innervated by the tibial division but is primarily a motor function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShort head of biceps femoris\u003C/strong\u003E - This is innervated by the common fibular division\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin over anterolateral leg\u003C/strong\u003E - This area is innervated by the common fibular nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHip and knee joints\u003C/strong\u003E - These joints receive sensory innervation from other nerves, not specifically the tibial division\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The tibial division of the sciatic nerve provides sensory innervation to the posterior compartment of the leg, excluding the short head of the biceps femoris.","The tibial division of the sciatic nerve does not provide sensory innervation to the skin over the anterolateral leg.","The tibial division of the sciatic nerve is responsible for innervating the hamstring portion of the adductor magnus."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Giuffre BA, Black AC, Jeanmonod R. Anatomy, Sciatic Nerve. 2023 Nov 16. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29494038."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63865"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18305"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63865"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T09:22:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T09:22:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11023"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78524"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt